@OurCofELike @mark_earey 5/ I give them a copy of what we may have decided. It’s not always finished. Offer to choose stuff only if they wish. All my details are on this sheet  with assurance of our prayers. Tell them about proofs of order of services & continually reassure. Smile & share their sadness

@OurCofELike @mark_earey 4/ Are there any thanks to say. Is there anything they may like to do at the graveside. I always say how after I’ve gone they will still have many questions. Happy to chat & to let them know that I’m not phased with last minute requests especially before service starts

@OurCofELike @mark_earey 3/ we then go through a possible order of service. This is guided but very much their wishes. My services are liturgy light but with an Anglican likeness. I ask if they would like a memorial candle lit if in church. Would they like to display a photo etc

@OurCofELike @mark_earey 2/ I then ask if anyone would like to say anything. If yes I take the ideas & names. If no I ask if anyone might like to write something biog etc. I give ideas & send a template by email if poss. I then draw a family tree finding how each refers to the person.

@OurCofELike @mark_earey 1/ The replies are fab. 

I start with the privilege & thanks for being able to meet. I meet with as many as want or need to be present. I always go to them. I usually accept the offer of a drink. I ask how the person is known & interchange these through the service.
